00:01:45.140 --> 00:01:46.340
So how did I do that?

00:01:46.340 --> 00:01:49.200
It wasn't magic at all,
it was a bit of mathematics, okay.

00:01:49.200 --> 00:01:51.380
So actually the message
sent by the computer

00:01:51.380 --> 00:01:54.260
isn't the whole thing but just
the top 4 by 4 block.

00:01:54.260 --> 00:01:56.720
So this is actually
the message they want to send,

00:01:56.720 --> 00:01:58.400
so I'm going to separate this off.

00:02:00.760 --> 00:02:05.160
So the message sent by the computer
is actually this top block here

00:02:05.160 --> 00:02:07.320
and the other digits
are used to keep check

00:02:07.320 --> 00:02:09.380
of what's happening
inside the message.

00:02:09.380 --> 00:02:11.840
and actually at the bottom here
if you look at the bottom column

00:02:11.840 --> 00:02:16.600
this number here will be a 1
if there are an odd number of 1s in this column.

00:02:16.600 --> 00:02:19.500
Okay, and if there are
an even number of 1s,

00:02:19.500 --> 00:02:22.140
so in this column,
I put a 0, okay.

00:02:22.140 --> 00:02:25.160
So when you turned
one of the things over,

00:02:25.160 --> 00:02:28.019
it didn't check out, so for example
if I turn that over

00:02:28.020 --> 00:02:30.600
then I've got, well they're meant to be
an even number of 1s there,

00:02:30.600 --> 00:02:32.720
so I know there's a mistake
in that column.

00:02:32.720 --> 00:02:35.260
